<img src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="720" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-544226 lazyload" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court.jpg 1280w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-640x360.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-1062x598.jpg 1062w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-320x180.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-281x158.jpg 281w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-562x316.jpg 562w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-531x299.jpg 531w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-487x274.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-974x548.jpg 974w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/court-600x338.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" />An Akure Chief Magistrates’ Court on Monday remanded 27- year-old Seidu-Shakiru Adeyemi in Olokuta prison for allegedly killing his 25-year-old girlfriend, Khadijat Oluboyo. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that Khadijat, the daughter of a former deputy governor of Ondo State, Alhaji Lasisi Oluboyo, was a final year student of Adekunle Ajasin University, Akungba-Akoko. She  was found dead in her boyfriend’s house on July 2. The Chief Magistrate, Mrs Victoria Bob-Manuel, ordered the remand of the accused in prison custody pending the receipt of legal advice from the State Director of Public Prosecution. Bob-Manuel ordered that the original copy of the case file be sent to the State Chief Registrar for safe keeping. Earlier, the prosecutor, Sgt. Mary Adebayo, had told the court that the accused person and others at large conspired together to strangulate Khadijat to death and buried her in his room. Read More: Boyfriend, Adeyemi narrates how slain Ondo ex-deputy governor’s daughter was killed According to prosecutor, the accused person committed the offence on July 2  at about 7:30 pm at Aratunsi St., Oke-Aro, Akure. She  said that the offence was contrary to and punishable under Sections 324 and 316 of the Criminal Code Cap. 37, Vol. I Laws of Ondo State of Nigeria, 2006. The plea of the accused was not taken, while the Chief Magistrate adjourned the case till Aug. 23 for receipt of the legal advice.  To enable commenting and other interactive features, please switch to the more advanced .